Thus the Aeneid, like some of the grandest sculptures of Michael Ange10, was left unfinished, and with some parts, perhaps, in the rough. But Ι am not sure that our interest is not even enhanced in the works of both of these great Italian masters by the very fact that these unfinished parts show us the hand, as it were, still holding the chisel, and in the act of creation.

There is another fault, tce. Vergil was an imitator. He gloried in imitation. He borrowed without stint from Homer, from Apolloniae, from the Greek tragedies, and, in short, he laid under contribution all the earlier poets both of Greece and of Rome. Nothing beautiful in them, nothing fitted to his purpose escaped his search. But he so appropriated to himself, and assimi- lated to his own modes of thought their ideae, imageS, and forms of expression, that they come before us in the Aeneid in all the freshness and individuality of new creatione. The Aeneid stands nearly in the same relation to all preexisting literature as does the “Paradise Lost.'' The authors of these two epics are the great- est of all plagiarists3 but the borrowed thought in both of them assumes so much of their individuality that their plagiarism becomes a beauty and a virtue. They are plagiarists of the older poets in the same sense that the painter is a plagiarist of nature. '

But while the Aeneid, through the premature death of the poet, has been left to us somewhat incomplete, and while it claims no great degree of originality, but is largely the offspring, not of Vergil alone, but of the genius of all antiquity, it always has been, and always will be, justly regarded as the best and noblest os all the poetic creatione of the Roman mind, and as one of the choicest productione of all literature. There are fashions in criticism as well as in other things3 not, indeed, so changeful and transitory as those of dress, but fashions nevertheless; and of late years some scholare, even eminent scholare, have fallen into the, habit or affectation of speaking with some contempt of “the court poets of the Augustan age.’' This fashion will have its day3 but it can not set aside the verdict of so many generations past.
